TY  - JOUR
AU  - Hu, Guili
AU  - Li, Cheng
AU  - Han, Fei
AU  - Kang, Ningbo
TI  - A framework for closed-loop intelligent control in food drying: A review and perspective
T2  - FOOD CONTROL
M3  - Article
AB  - Food drying is a critical operation in agricultural processing. However, achieving high-quality and energyefficient drying on an industrial scale is hindered by the challenge of "black-box" monitoring, which stems from material biological variability, thermal sensitivity, and strong process coupling. To address this challenge, multimodal sensor fusion technology presents a potential pathway through the integration of machine vision, optical, dielectric, and chemical sensing methods. This integration facilitates the simultaneous acquisition of multidimensional information, including material morphology, internal composition, and flavor profiles during drying, thereby helping to mitigate the limitations inherent in single-mode sensing.Coupled with artificial intelligence (AI) algorithms, it further facilitates the development of intelligent closed-loop control strategies. This review systematically outlines multi-sensor technologies for food drying, detailing their principles, applications, and limitations. It then examines core mechanisms of multimodal data fusion, including spatiotemporal alignment, dynamic weighting, complementary design, and conflict resolution. The subsequent section reviews intelligent control strategies such as model predictive control, neuro-fuzzy systems, and data-driven algorithms, analyzing their potential and challenges in optimizing drying processes through fused data. Case studies are employed to objectively identify key bottlenecks in sensor adaptability, model generalization, and system integration. Finally, emerging directions like bio-inspired sensing, edge intelligence, digital twins, and explainable artificial intelligence are highlighted. To this end, the review underscores that establishing unified performance metrics and conducting cost-benefit analyses are crucial for their practical implementation, thereby offering a systematic reference to guide the future development of intelligent food drying.
