TI  - Comparative study on cold plasma technologies for mold inactivation and quality retention in white grapes
T2  - FOOD CONTROL
M3  - Article
AB  - White grapes (Vitis vinifera) are valued for their flavour and nutrition, but they spoil quickly, often due to Botrytis cinerea. Recently, cold atmospheric pressure plasma (CAPP) has gained attention as a clean and more efficient way for food sterilization. This study compares the efficacy of three CAPP technologies, i.e., cold Atmospheric Plasma Jet (CAPJ), Dielectric Barrier Discharge (DBD) roller system, and Plasma Activated Water (PAW) for mold inactivation and quality retention in white grapes. CAPJ and DBD treatments achieved complete microbial and mold inactivation below detection limits, whereas PAW treatments (15 min) reduced the total aerobic count by 2.4 log CFU/mL and eliminated mold growth. The results showed that both CAPJ and the DBD plasma reactor effectively destroy the structure of mold, impacting its metabolism and leading to significant accumulation of reactive oxygen and nitrogen species (RONS), thereby inducing redox imbalances. SEM results demonstrated extensive morphological deterioration of fungal spores after CAPJ and DBD treatments, supporting their enhanced antifungal performance. CAPJ-treated grapes showed the most significant elevation in phenolics and flavonoids due to plasma-mediated release. Key physicochemical metrics, including soluble solids, ascorbic acid, and colour, remained essentially unchanged (Delta E < 3.0). FTIR profiles displayed no new chemical bonds, and proton NMR confirmed intact metabolites, indicating minimal structural impact. The findings demonstrate that cold plasma technologies, particularly CAPJ and DBD systems, effectively inactivate Botrytis cinerea while maintaining the nutritional and sensory quality of grapes, highlighting their potential for safe, eco-friendly postharvest preservation.
