AU  - Lu, Yuyun
TI  - The potential of transforming dried noni fruit slurry into novel functional beverages with selected probiotic lactic acid bacteria
T2  - FOOD BIOSCIENCE
M3  - Article
AB  - Noni fruit is a tropical fruit with multiple purported health benefits but its flavor is generally undesirable (bitter taste and pungent odor). This study explored the potential of using dried noni fruit slurry (DNFS; prepared by suspending dried noni fruit powder in water followed by extraction under mild agitation) as a substrate for probiotic fermentation, with a focus on its impacts on nutritional composition and flavor profiles. Four probiotic lactic acid bacteria (Lactiplantibacillus plantarum 299v, Lacticaseibacillus casei Shirota, Lacticaseibacillus rhamnosus GG, and Lactobacillus acidophilus La-14) were evaluated. All strains grew well in DNFS, reaching viable counts exceeding 8.8 log CFU/mL from approximately 7.0 log CFU/mL in 24 h. Fermentation led to a significant increase in lactic acid (up to 14.28 g/L), along with elevated levels of key volatile compounds such as 3-methyl-3-buten-1-ol (up to 214.94 mu g/L) and 2-phenylethyl alcohol (up to 164.96 mu g/L). Antioxidant-related phenolic and iridoid compounds, including rutin (9.93 and 9.79 mg/L, respectively), chlorogenic acid (4.99 and 4.86 mg/L, respectively) and deacetylasperulosidic acid (DAA, 451.8 and 420.3 mg/L, respectively), were either maintained or increased in DNFS fermented with L. plantarum 299v and L. rhamnosus GG at 48 h. However, a slight reduction in total phenolic content (from 8.21 to 6.67-7.42 mmol gallic acid equivalent/L) was observed during fermentation. These findings highlight the potential of DNFS as a viable base for probiotic beverage development. Further research is needed to optimize fermentation parameters and sensory characteristics to boost consumer acceptance.
