TI  - Quality and Acceptability of Reconstituted Spray Dried Yoghurt-Ice Cream Mix
T2  - PHILIPPINE AGRICULTURAL SCIENTIST
M3  - Article
AB  - Physico-chemical and microbiological qualities of yoghurt-ice cream mix before and after the spray drying process were determined and the acceptability of yoghurt-ice cream from the reconstituted spray dried mix was evaluated.Acidity (0.61% lactic acid) and pH (5.33) values obtained for reconstituted yoghurt-ice cream mix were not significantly different from the values obtained prior to spray drying, unlike total viable yoghurt bacterial count, acetaldehyde, fat content and total soluble solids which were significantly different. Acetaldehyde content (9 ppm), which imparts yoghurt flavor, was still within the acceptable range of 8-50 ppm. Fat content (2.63%) slightly exceeded the maximum standard for low-fat frozen yoghurt (2.0%). Scanning electron micrographs showed disruption of fat globules which reduced desirable creamy flavor of the final product. The bacterial count decreased significantly from 3.50 x 10(7) cfu mL(-1) for Lactobacillus bulgaricus and 4.10 x 10(8) cfu mL(-1) for Streptococcus thermophilus to 3.33 x 10(1) cfu mL(-1) and 3.67 x 10(1) cfu mL(-1) respectively. Based on the Codex standard for frozen yoghurt, the required viability and abundance of yoghurt bacteria do not apply to products subjected to heat treatment after fermentation.Sensory evaluation showed that the final yoghurt-ice cream product from the spray dried mix was acceptable with mean score of 11 out of 15 (highly acceptable).
